(This definition is justified by the following calculation, itself justified by the Yoneda lemma: if $x\in C$ is of the form $p(y)$, then $p(x)=p^2(y)=p(y)=x$.)

\begin{lemma}\phantomsection\label{l:retr} Suppose that $p$ has an image. Then  is canonically a retract of $C$.
\begin{equation}{\boldsymbol{\mathcal{D}}}\longleftrightarrow \text{\textit{$D_j$}}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol x}_{\text{\textit{$g$}}}|\,\tilde{\boldsymbol x}_s;\text{\textit{$t$}}\right).\end{equation}
\end{lemma}

\begin{proof} By definition, we have a canonical morphism $p\to C$ equalising the~two arrows $1_X,p$. Conversely, the endomorphism $p:C\to C$ equalises these two arrows, and thus factors canonically through $p$. We immediately see that the composition
\begin{equation*}\vspace*{-3pt}
p\to C\to p\vspace*{-3pt}
\end{equation*}
is equal to the identity.
\end{proof}


