\begin{theorem}\label{tA.2} A Karoubi envelope always exists: the functor $i$ is fully faithful and the functor  $($the Karoubi envelope of $)$ is an equivalence of categories.
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}
One may find two proofs in \cite{SGA4}: one in Exercise 7.5 of expos\'e IV and the other in Exercise 8.7.8 from expos\'e I. We give the first proof, which has the advantage of being constructive (the second, which uses ind-objects, is more conceptual).

Define a category  whose objects are the pairs $(C,p)$ where $C\in $ and $p$ is a projector of $C$. For another object $(D,q)$, we define:
\begin{equation*}
((C,p),(D,q))=\{f\in (C,D)\mid f=qfp\}.
\end{equation*}

The composition of morphisms is induced by that of ; the identity of $(C,p)$ is $p$. The functor $i$ is defined by
\begin{equation*}
i(C)=(C,1_C)
\end{equation*}
and $i$ is the identity on morphisms. The universal property can be easily verified, which then implies the last statement.
\end{proof}

